{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649549"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18363"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.14,0.64,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11081"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59862"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7466"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25703"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe human foot is composed of several types of bones, including tarsals, metatarsals, and phalanges. These bones work together to provide support and mobility.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of bones is the most numerous in the human foot?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metatarsals","Tarsals","Phalanges","Sesamoids","Calcaneus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003EPhalanges\u003C/strong\u003E. The human foot contains 14 phalanges, making them the most numerous type of bone in the foot. Each toe has three phalanges, except for the big toe, which has two.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetatarsals\u003C/strong\u003E - There are five metatarsal bones in each foot.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETarsals\u003C/strong\u003E - There are seven tarsal bones in each foot.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESesamoids\u003C/strong\u003E - There are typically two sesamoid bones in each foot, located under the big toe.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcaneus\u003C/strong\u003E - The calcaneus is a single bone in each foot, also known as the heel bone.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The human foot contains 26 bones, which include the tarsals, metatarsals, and phalanges.","The phalanges are the most numerous bones in the foot, with a total of 14 bones.","Each toe has three phalanges, except for the big toe, which has two."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","i